The iudices in criminal causes were generally appointed by sortitio: that is, the president of the quaestio drew out of an urn containing the names of all his iudices (selecti) the number necessary for the trial: the parties were allowed to challenge a certain proporfion, in whose place other names were drawn (subsortitio). In this ballot the praetor had opportunities for foul play. The praetor's urna here may be that used sor this purpose or rather that in which the tablets A (absolvo), C (condemno), or N L (non liquet) were thrown. If the first, the praetor has packed the jury. cf. Aen.
